A Bond Between Generations

Female bonobos exhibit profound maternal instincts, nurturing their young for several years, often nursing them until they reach the age of five or six. In this serene moment, a mother finds solace on the forest floor while her baby drinks.

Capturing these intimate scenes is a rare privilege, as wild bonobos, our closest living relatives, inhabit only the dense tropical forests south of the Congo River in Central Africa.

For nearly three decades, dedicated German researchers from the Max-Planck-Institute for Animal Behavior, Barbara Fruth and her husband Gottfried Hohmann, have devoted themselves to the study of wild bonobos. Their extensive commitment spans nearly 30 years, with 18 years spent at Lui Kotale, next to Salonga N.P in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).

Join us on this journey of understanding and preservation as we share the remarkable story of these extraordinary primates in their natural habitat.

